ShinyFruit Tutorial

ShinyFruit is an R-based application that is currently capable of analyzing images of small fruits. It was created using the shiny package, and is currently capable of measuring fruit size (length, width, and area) and color defects. The best way to run this application is to install via R directly from the GitHub page and run locally. Follow this guide to get started!

Any qustions, feedback, or suggestions for new features can be directed to mchizk1@gmail.com

Step 1. Install R

Find and install the most recent version for your operating system here

Step 2. Install devtools package

devtools is a great package that provides functions for MANY things. One such thing is to allow users to easily install R packages that are maintained on GitHub, rather than the official CRAN repository. devtools can be installed by running the following line of code into the R console.

install.packages("devtools")

Step 3. Install ShinyFruit from GitHub

ShinyFruit can be installed by simply running the following line of code in the R console.

devtools::install_github("mchizk1/ShinyFruit")

Beyond its installation, the source code, open issues, and current version can be found directly on my GitHub repo

Step 4. Running ShinyFruit locally

Run the following line of code in the R console

ShinyFruit::ShinyFruit()

This function, with no arguments provided, should open the user interface shown below

The initial user interface

Step 5. Load sample image

Interacting with the browser button should open the file search dialog. There are a few general rules that should be followed when collecting images for ShinyFruit analysis:

  • jpg is currently the only supported format. I will probably add support for others like png in the future.
  • inclusion of a known size standard is highly recommended (allows useful size analysis)
  • If multiple pictures are taken, lighting conditions and camera height should be kept as consistent as possible, such that filters used on image A still apply to images B-Z
  • Test images should be in their own dedicated folder with no other irrelevant files or subfolders.
  • Size analysis assumes that fruit are oriented with the top facing away from the photographer.
  • Having at least half and inch of spacing between fruits should help ensure that the fruit is counted correctly and independently.
  • The background should not contain any color that may potentially be found on the fruit itself.

After opening a sample image

Step 6. Set size standard (optional but highly recommended)

If a size standard is present in the sample image, click on the relevant switch. This should open up a couple new options for data entry.

With a size reference included

Step 7. Crop out the size standard (only if provided)

If a size standard is provided, there is a good chance that it will interfere with the analysis unless it is cropped out entirely. For this reason, it is recommended to always have the size reference present in the same part of the picture. The settings for cropping, like all other settings, will applied to all images in a batch analysis.

Cropped reference

Step 8. Filter out background area

Before conducting the analysis, the user must define the color thresholds that should be used to remove the background from the image. This step requires some experimentation, but if images were taken in a consistent way, there should be an effective threshold that can be applied to all images in the set. In addition, there is support for multiple color spaces to experiment with. If RGB thresholds dont work well for the image, try Lab or HSB! Future updates will add even more color spaces for more flexible thresholding options.

Removing background area

Step 9. Select traits for analysis!!!

Finally! Heres the fun part

Setting options for analysis

Step 10. Run the batch analysis

All current settings will be applied to all images in the selected input directory. Including images in the output data will slow down the analysis, but will provide the user with a chance to visually check the quality of the analyis against the original images. All the data requested will be included in a single output csv file, with each image representing a row and each column representing a trait.

Running the batch analysis
